Excited to announce that Let Them Kids Be Kids is headed to New York! Join me next Saturday February 11 from 6-9 PM for the opening reception & tell a friend to tell a friend.

Let Them Kids Be Kids uses the school and playground as a framework with which to examine the joys of Black childhood and the ways in which issues of race equity, and politics are inscribed on the site. Employing images from her personal life to examine these ideas, Lex Marie’s paintings and installations address the issue of adultification bias as she makes the case that all children have a right to innocence.

School Supplies 
4 of 5 
.
I never publicly shared the reason I chose to originally make this piece. In short, picking up my Kindergartner from school last year and him telling me about an emergency drill he did where him and his classmates hid in the bathroom and the teacher came in and they had to remain quiet to not get caught, really did a number on me. And like most of my work, this piece was a way for me to express my frustration as a mother and to bring awareness to the many problems children are facing that seem to be becoming normalized. Im hoping the work will start conversations in the art world and in the homes of those who collect or see my work. 

+And on that note I’m wishing the babies a happy and safe school year 💛
My lil chicken nugget turned 6 and started 1st grade 🧡 I am such a proud mama.

Cierra Britton Gallery is pleased to announce our fall presentation, A Color Story, opening October 5th from 6pm-8pm featuring the work of Lindsay Adams, Nola Ayoola, Quinci Baker, Kwamé Gomez, Lewinale Havette, and Lex Marie.⁠
⁠
A Color Story is an exhibition exploring color theory in relation to narrative and symbolism. This show features artists who employ color-dominant and monochromatic palettes as an intentional method throughout their work across a range of styles including abstraction, figuration, textiles, and flora. This presentation unearths the ways that color can hold and shape narratives that resonate in specific ways depending on the viewer. ⁠
⁠
Color has a tendency to evoke a range of emotional and sensational experiences, based on the individual, whether conjuring memories and affecting our subconscious, or reminding us of feelings, places, and people. The works in A Color Story reflect on how different color associations have informed a range of our personal and communal stories, from love stories to looking at the public school-to-prison pipeline.⁠

Please join us at our opening reception on Thursday, October 5th from 6pm-8pm at our Dumbo pop-up space located at 202b Plymouth Street, Brooklyn NY.

Very excited to share Waving the White Flag has been acquired by the District of Columbia CAH Art Bank collection FY 2024. This is my 2nd work joining this collection (Graduation Day was acquired in 23’) and I particularly enjoy being a part of this collection because the work acquired is kept in DC and shown publicly in its government buildings. “Graduation Day” is currently placed at the Office of Gun Violence Prevention” and if you follow my work you know this is a cause dear to me. 

Thank you DCCAH for your continuous support of local artists. These acquisitions are pivotal in helping artists sustain their practice and helps makes our work more accessible to our communities.
